Sickle cell disease.

Lane PA(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Pediatrics, University of Colorado School of Medicine, Denver, 
USA.

The identification of genetic mutation that causes sickle cell disease 35 years 
ago has not yet led to a widely applicable, specific therapy that corrects the 
underlying abnormality of hemoglobin. Nevertheless, recent progress in 
understanding the pathophysiology and natural history of sickling disorders has 
led directly to important prophylactic and supportive therapies that have 
markedly reduced morbidity and prolonged life expectancy. This is particularly 
true for manifestations of sickle cell disease that result from damage to the 
spleen, lungs, and brain. New strategies for specific therapy, including 
expanded use of chronic transfusions, bone marrow transplantation, and 
hydroxyurea, now offer hope for prevention of many or all of the hemolytic and 
vaso-occlusive manifestations of sickle cell disease.

